  <li id="comment-6117" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/07280224924513302940" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Anna</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=1501#comment-6117"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2007-04-03T17:36:00-04:00">Tuesday, April 3, 2007 at 5:36 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Should you need to open a coconut again, here&#8217;s the best method I&#8217;ve found. When I was a kid, my dad would sometimes bring home a coconut as a treat and I would painstakingly pry the meat out of the shell with a butter knife, but since then I&#8217;ve discovered a much improved (lazy) way to do it:</></>Use a hammer and nail to punch holes in 2 of the coconut&#8217;s 3 &#8220;eyes,&#8221; and drain the juice out. Bake the whole coconut in the oven (about 20 minutes at about 350 degrees F); this may make the smoke detector go off, so be warned! Then put the coconut in a plastic bag and smash it with a hammer. The meat shrinks in the oven and comes right off the shell.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?p=1501#comment-6117' data-commentid="6117" data-postid="1501" data-belowelement="comment-6117" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Anna" aria-label='Reply to Anna'>Reply</a>    </div>
